  "local_port": 39988,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What can I do with an infant at Walt Disney World?",
  "response": "Taking an infant to Walt Disney World can be a magical experience for both you and your little one. Here are some tips and activities to consider during your visit:\n\n1. **Rider Switch**: If you're visiting with another adult or older children who want to go on rides that aren't suitable for infants, utilize the Rider Switch program. This allows one adult to wait with the baby while the other rides, and then switch without waiting in line again.\n\n2. **Baby Care Centers**: Each park has a Baby Care Center equipped with changing tables, nursing rooms, high chairs, and areas to rest. They're a nice break from the hustle and bustle of the parks.\n\n3. **Stroller Rentals**: Consider renting a stroller either from the park or from a third-party company, as you\u2019ll cover a lot of ground. A stroller provides a comfortable place for your infant to rest.\n\n4. **Suitable Rides and Attractions**: While many rides have height requirements, there are plenty of attractions suitable for all ages. Look for gentle rides like \"It\u2019s a Small World,\" \"The Many Adventures of Winnie the Pooh,\" \"Dumbo the Flying Elephant,\" and \"Under the Sea \u2013 Journey of the Little Mermaid.\"\n\n5. **Character Meet-and-Greets**: Although your infant might not remember meeting Mickey or Minnie Mouse, these can be great photo opportunities and memorable keepsakes for you.\n\n6. **Parades and Shows**: Find a comfortable spot to watch parades and shows, which are visually stimulating and entertaining for infants.\n\n7. **Fireworks**: While they may be a bit loud, the fireworks shows are dazzling. Consider ear protection for your infant to reduce the noise.\n\n8. **Keep a Flexible Schedule**: Infants need naps, regular feedings, and downtime, so plan a flexible schedule to accommodate your baby's needs. Consider returning to your hotel for a nap or early bedtime.\n\n9. **Shaded Areas and Breaks**: Florida can get hot, so keep your infant cool in shaded areas and take frequent breaks to rest and hydrate.\n\n10. **Pack Essentials**: Bring plenty of diapers, wipes, snacks, and extra clothes, as well as any special items your baby needs, such as pacifiers or formula.\n\nOverall, with a little planning and a flexible mindset, you can have a wonderful time exploring Walt Disney World with your infant.",
